\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {VI}{\ignorespaces Cross-model replication: embedding regret bias (37 models, 7 families; all batches combined). $d_\text  {DN}$/$d_\text  {CN}$: Cohen's $d$ vs.\ neutral (two-sample pooled-SD); 95\% CI from 1{,}000 bootstrap resamples. All 37 models show D$>$N. $n$ = total per model. All 37 models are fully stable ($\qopname  \relax m{min}(n_D,n_N)\geq 30$; batch v36 upgraded GPT-5, GPT-5-nano, GPT-5.1, and GPT-5.2 from near-stability to full stability; batch v33 upgraded o1/o3 to $n_N=30$). \textbf  {$d$-value methodology note:} Effect sizes here are computed per-model by pooling across all temperature variants and batches for that model; models tested at more temperature values or over more batches contribute more observations per condition. Some models (e.g., GPT-5.4 full: $d=4.96$; GPT-4.1-nano: $d=4.63$) show inflated $d$ relative to primary-batch estimates ($d=0.42$--$1.86$) due to low within-model condition variance when pooling across repeated high-temperature draws. Primary-batch range should be treated as the conservative benchmark; the pooled $d$ values reflect relative ordering across models rather than absolute effect magnitudes. This table is descriptive alongside the confirmatory LME ($N=7{,}440$; Table\nobreakspace  {}IV\hbox {}).}}{11}{}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:multimodel}{{VI}{11}}
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {VII}{\ignorespaces Minimal-pair ablation: semantic regret bias by topic ($N=196$). D=deprivation, CF=counterfactual, N=neutral; $d$ is Cohen's $d$ vs.\ neutral (pooled-SD; neutral $SD=0$ for all topics---see note). $\dagger $Per-topic $d$ inflated: neutral $SD=0$ causes pooled $SD$ to equal treatment $SD$; combined $d$ uses cross-topic pooling.}}{12}{}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:ablation_topic}{{VII}{12}}
